1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,200
March 4th, 2022. 3:00 AM. Park City, Utah.

2
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:13,300
Kouri Richins places a frantic 911 call. Her husband, Eric, is unresponsive in their bed. Paramedics arrive within minutes.

3
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:15,500
It's too late.

4
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:22,600
Eric Richins, 39 years old, father of three, is pronounced dead at the scene.

5
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:31,000
The cause of death?  Fentanyl poisoning.  Five times the lethal dose.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,200
But this wasn't an accidental overdose. Eric didn't use drugs.  He was murdered.

7
00:00:43,700 --> 00:00:48,900
And the person who killed him?  The woman who called 911.  His wife.

8
00:00:51,900 --> 00:00:53,500
This is Mind Crimes.

9
00:00:55,500 --> 00:01:05,500
Today, we're examining one of the most disturbing cases of 2026. A case that combines financial desperation, narcissistic manipulation, and the weaponization of grief itself.

10
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:15,599
Kouri Richins. A Utah mother of three. Real estate investor. And, as of March 16th, 2026,  a convicted murderer.

11
00:01:17,599 --> 00:01:29,599
But before we get to the murder, we need to understand who Kouri and Eric Richins were, and how their seemingly perfect life was built on a foundation of lies.

12
00:01:32,599 --> 00:01:47,399
Kouri and Eric Richins met in their twenties and married in 2013. They settled in the affluent ski town of Park City, Utah, a place known for its mountain views, luxury homes, and the Sundance Film Festival.

13
00:01:48,899 --> 00:02:02,499
Eric came from a successful family. His parents owned a masonry business, and Eric himself was a skilled stone mason. He was described by friends as hardworking, loyal, and devoted to his three sons.

14
00:02:03,999 --> 00:02:18,799
Kouri, on the other hand, was ambitious. She started a real estate business flipping houses. Buying properties, renovating them, and selling for profit. On social media, she portrayed herself as a successful businesswoman living the American dream.

15
00:02:21,299 --> 00:02:23,699
But the reality  was far different.

16
00:02:26,199 --> 00:02:38,199
Court documents revealed that Kouri's real estate empire was collapsing. Her business was losing money. By 2022, she was in debt to the tune of seven point five million dollars.

17
00:02:41,199 --> 00:02:51,199
A forensic accountant who testified at trial described her finances as "imploding." Her net worth the day after Eric's death?  Negative one point six million.

18
00:02:53,199 --> 00:03:03,199
But Eric didn't know the full extent of the problem. Kouri kept him in the dark about the mounting debts, failed investments, and financial chaos.

19
00:03:05,699 --> 00:03:10,099
What Eric did know was this:  he didn't trust his wife.

20
00:03:13,099 --> 00:03:23,500
By early 2022, Eric Richins was becoming suspicious. He noticed irregularities in their finances. He questioned Kouri's spending. And he began taking steps to protect himself.

21
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:38,199
In February 2022, Eric changed his will. He removed Kouri as a beneficiary, placing his assets into a trust for his three sons. He also confided in friends that his marriage was struggling.

22
00:03:41,699 --> 00:03:45,299
But Kouri had other plans.  Plans that involved fentanyl.

23
00:03:48,299 --> 00:03:50,299
February 14th, 2022. Valentine's Day.

24
00:03:51,799 --> 00:04:04,599
Kouri and Eric go out to dinner. According to court testimony, Kouri had recently acquired hydrocodone pills from an acquaintance, a housekeeper named Carmen Lauber, who lived at a sober living facility.

25
00:04:06,599 --> 00:04:18,600
But hydrocodone wasn't strong enough. Kouri wanted something more lethal. She specifically requested  "some of the Michael Jackson" stuff. A reference to fentanyl, the drug that killed the pop star.

26
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:34,400
After Valentine's dinner, Eric became violently ill. He told friends he believed his wife had tried to poison him. He even said the words out loud:  "Kouri is trying to kill me."

27
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:41,800
But he didn't go to the police.  And he didn't leave.

28
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:54,600
Two weeks after the Valentine's Day incident, Kouri went back to Carmen Lauber. This time, she got what she wanted:  fentanyl pills.

29
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:07,000
Text messages recovered by investigators show Kouri picking up the drugs on February 26th, 2022.  Six days later,  Eric was dead.

30
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:22,399
On the night of March 4th, Kouri and Eric celebrated closing a real estate deal. Kouri mixed Eric a Moscow Mule, a cocktail made with vodka, ginger beer, and lime juice.

31
00:05:23,899 --> 00:05:26,699
She brought it to him in bed.

32
00:05:30,199 --> 00:05:33,800
Eric drank it.  And within hours,  he was dead.

33
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:49,199
Medical examiners found five times the lethal dose of fentanyl in his system. The amount, prosecutors later argued, showed that Kouri Richins wanted Eric  "not only dead, but good and dead."

34
00:05:53,199 --> 00:05:58,000
Most people who commit murder try to lay low.  Not Kouri Richins.

35
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:14,399
In March 2023, one year after her husband's death, Kouri self-published a children's book titled "Are You with Me?" The book was marketed as a way to help children cope with grief after losing a parent.

36
00:06:15,899 --> 00:06:26,299
Kouri appeared on local TV, smiling and promoting the book. She talked about how much she missed Eric. She described their marriage as loving and supportive.

37
00:06:29,799 --> 00:06:35,399
It was a masterclass in narcissistic manipulation.  And it made investigators even more suspicious.

38
00:06:38,399 --> 00:06:41,599
Behind the scenes, detectives were building a case.

39
00:06:43,099 --> 00:07:01,099
They interviewed Carmen Lauber, the woman who sold Kouri the fentanyl. They analyzed Kouri's phone records. They dug into her finances. The seven point five million dollar debt. The collapsing real estate business. The one point four million dollar life insurance policy on Eric's life.

40
00:07:04,099 --> 00:07:08,499
And they uncovered something else:  Kouri had been having an affair.

41
00:07:10,999 --> 00:07:22,999
Testimony at trial revealed that Kouri had been involved with another man during her marriage. Prosecutors argued she wanted to leave Eric, but she didn't want to leave his money.

42
00:07:24,999 --> 00:07:33,799
As Chief Prosecutor Brad Bloodworth put it:  "She wanted to leave Eric Richins, but she did not want to leave his money."

43
00:07:37,799 --> 00:07:42,999
The motive was clear:  financial desperation, plus affair, plus life insurance,  equals murder.

44
00:07:44,999 --> 00:07:50,199
On May 8th, 2023, Kouri Richins was arrested and charged with aggravated murder.

45
00:07:53,199 --> 00:07:57,999
The trial began in February 2026, nearly four years after Eric's death.

46
00:07:59,499 --> 00:08:28,699
Prosecutors presented a mountain of evidence. Text messages between Kouri and Carmen Lauber discussing drug purchases. Testimony from Eric's friends, who said he believed Kouri was trying to poison him. Financial records showing Kouri's seven point five million dollar debt. Cell phone data placing Kouri at the drug pickup location. Forensic evidence showing five times the lethal dose of fentanyl in Eric's system. Testimony from the man Kouri was having an affair with.

47
00:08:30,699 --> 00:08:39,499
The defense argued that Eric could have overdosed accidentally, that the drug dealer was unreliable, and that the prosecution's case was circumstantial.

48
00:08:40,999 --> 00:08:42,999
But the jury wasn't convinced.

49
00:08:45,999 --> 00:08:52,399
On March 16th, 2026, after just over three hours of deliberation, the jury returned a verdict:

50
00:08:55,399 --> 00:08:56,999
Guilty of aggravated murder.

51
00:08:57,999 --> 00:08:59,999
Guilty of attempted aggravated murder.

52
00:08:59,999 --> 00:09:02,399
Guilty of forgery and insurance fraud.

53
00:09:04,399 --> 00:09:08,399
Kouri Richins showed no emotion as the verdict was read.

54
00:09:09,899 --> 00:09:12,699
She faces life in prison without parole.

55
00:09:16,699 --> 00:09:21,099
The Kouri Richins case is a textbook example of narcissistic manipulation.

56
00:09:22,599 --> 00:09:33,799
She constructed a public persona of the grieving widow. She wrote a children's book about loss. She appeared on television talking about how much she loved her husband.

57
00:09:35,799 --> 00:09:40,999
All while knowing she had poisoned him with a lethal dose of fentanyl.

58
00:09:44,999 --> 00:10:02,999
Psychologists who study cases like this point to a pattern: narcissists don't just commit crimes,  they perform them. They need the world to see them as victims, as heroes, as martyrs. The grief book wasn't just a cover story.  It was part of the performance.

59
00:10:06,499 --> 00:10:17,299
But in the end, the performance fell apart. The text messages, the financial records, the testimony from people who saw through the facade,  it all added up.

60
00:10:19,299 --> 00:10:27,699
Three children are now without both parents. Eric is dead. And Kouri will spend the rest of her life in prison.

61
00:10:32,699 --> 00:10:41,899
This case reminds us that the most dangerous people aren't always the ones who look dangerous.  Sometimes,  they're the ones who look perfect.

62
00:10:44,899 --> 00:10:58,499
Thank you for watching Mind Crimes. If you found this case as disturbing as I did, please subscribe and share this video. And if you have suggestions for future cases, leave a comment below.

63
00:11:00,499 --> 00:11:01,699
Until next time.

